d energize a movement. Praxis for the Poor offers a critical reflection on their work and builds upon it, demonstrating how a more politically-engaged scholarship can contribute to the struggle for social justice. Necessary reading for political scientists, sociologists, social workers, social welfare activists, policy-makers, and anyone concerned with the plight of the poor and oppressed, Praxis for the Poor shows how social science can play a role in building a better future for social welfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitical socializationzUnited States. 0aPovertyxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited States. 0aSocial justicezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aSchram, Sanford F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoss, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479817140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814786642.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814786642/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK